	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />How does the Snes convert 15-bit RGB into an NTSC/PAL signal?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>blargg</b> [ Thu Jun 03, 2010 6:11 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />At a basic level, I believe it converts the 15-bit RGB to YUV, uses the UV to adjust the phase and amplitude of the color carrier sine wave, yielding chroma, adds Y to that, attenuates based on the brightness register, adds sync information, and outputs. That is, I don't think there's any filtering applied to Y before it's mixed with the chroma. Every scanline it shifts the color carrier phase 120 degrees, unlike the usual 180 degrees. The above yields a result similar to the NES in its artifacts.
<br />
<br />I guess the above is kind of obvious, as that's what it would pretty much have to do. Why do you ask?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
