	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">At a basic level, I believe it converts the 15-bit RGB to YUV, uses the UV to adjust the phase and amplitude of the color carrier sine wave, yielding chroma, adds Y to that, attenuates based on the brightness register, adds sync information, and outputs. That is, I don't think there's any filtering applied to Y before it's mixed with the chroma. Every scanline it shifts the color carrier phase 120 degrees, unlike the usual 180 degrees. The above yields a result similar to the NES in its artifacts.<br /><br />I guess the above is kind of obvious, as that's what it would pretty much have to do. Why do you ask?</div>
<br />
<br />For some odd reason, I expected it did it some non traditional way, that involved converting RGB to the wave height at 0 degrees, 120 degrees, and 240 degrees and cycling through the 3 phases.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
